Start with `fgets`. That will save you from problems with newline characters. Remember to check for errors.

    #define SIZE 200
    char buf[SIZE];
    if (!fgets(buf, SIZE, stdin)) { 
        /* Something went wrong during reading */ 
    }

An extra check could be to see if the input is too long to fit, but I&#39;ll skip that. Then we read the float.

    if(sscanf(buf, &quot;%f&quot;, &amp;y) != 1) { 
        /* Something went wrong */ 
    }

Now `y` have been assigned a float number. So how do we check if the *user entered decimals*? This question is very different from what you are trying to check. What you&#39;re trying to do can fail for several reasons. Rounding errors is one of them. So we can do something like this.

    size_t len = strlen(buf);
    for(size_t i=0; i&lt;len; i++) {
        if(buf[i] == &#39;.&#39;) { 
            /* The user entered a decimal point */ 
        }
    }

Of course, you will have to replace the comments with appropriate error handling.

Your code (when corrected, for instance by Some programmer dude&#39;s answer) will fail for the input `1.0000001` for instance.

